---
import GlossaryEntry from '../../layouts/GlossaryEntry.astro';
---
<GlossaryEntry
  category="ESP32 Feature"
  title="DAC"
  subtitle="Digital-to-Analogue Converter"
  backTo="/guides/pam8403-esp32-audio#dac"
  backLabel="Back"
  highlights={[
    'GPIO25 -> DAC1 (used in PAM8403 guide)',
    'GPIO26 -> DAC2',
    '8-bit resolution: 0 = 0V, 128 = 1.65V, 255 = 3.3V',
    'dacWrite(25, value) - sets output instantly',
    '8kHz sample rate = 8000 writes per second',
  ]}
>
  <svg slot="svg" viewBox="0 0 320 160" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" style="width:100%;max-width:320px;display:block;margin:auto">
    <rect x="10" y="40" width="80" height="80" rx="6" fill="#1e1e2e" stroke="#4a4a6a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="50" y="86" fill="#e8a020" font-size="14" font-family="monospace" text-anchor="middle" font-weight="bold">128</text>
    <text x="50" y="101" fill="#666" font-size="8" font-family="monospace" text-anchor="middle">0 - 255</text>
    <line x1="90" y1="80" x2="118" y2="80" stroke="#555" stroke-width="2"/>
    <polygon points="116,75 124,80 116,85" fill="#555"/>
    <rect x="124" y="28" width="80" height="104" rx="6" fill="#2a1840" stroke="#8844cc" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="164" y="68" fill="#cc88ff" font-size="11" font-family="monospace" text-anchor="middle" font-weight="bold">DAC</text>
    <line x1="204" y1="80" x2="230" y2="80" stroke="#555" stroke-width="2"/>
    <polygon points="228,75 236,80 228,85" fill="#555"/>
    <rect x="236" y="36" width="74" height="88" rx="6" fill="#1a2a1a" stroke="#2ecc71" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <path d="M244 80 Q250 50 256 80 Q262 110 268 80 Q274 50 280 80 Q286 110 292 80 Q298 50 304 80" fill="none" stroke="#2ecc71" stroke-width="2.5"/>
    <text x="273" y="115" fill="#2ecc71" font-size="8" font-family="monospace" text-anchor="middle">0 - 3.3V</text>
  </svg>
  <Fragment slot="desc">
    <p>A DAC converts a digital number (0-255) into an analogue voltage (0-3.3V). The ESP32 has two: GPIO25 (DAC1) and GPIO26 (DAC2).</p>
    <p>Audio works by writing thousands of sample values per second - each number sets an exact voltage level, and the rapid succession of levels forms a waveform that the amplifier drives into the speaker.</p>
  </Fragment>
</GlossaryEntry>
